text: Even if Freudian psychoanalysis, psychotherapy, etc. fist appears as scandalous and disturbing at times, it seems when developed to its logical conclusions as in Dr. Alexander Lowen, it ends up very moderate and sensible. Lowen also is a follower of Dr. Hans Selye just like Peat.

The endgame of Lowenian therapy is just disentangling physicality from sexuality so practically it ends up with the most pleasant and bourgeois advice: getting a massage (non-erotically), practicing penmanship/handwriting, nuzzling your loved ones, doing Pilates, stretching, etc.
The most important thing is going on a long vacation on occasion.

"Thou art power. Who could tell you what to do or not to do?" All conditioned existence is Shakti's "game" and unrestrained play. Lalita as a goddess is also portrayed as a 14 year old girl. It seems H.H.'s perspective in the book is him being "manipulated" as Lolita's plaything.

This struck me when reading bar. Julius Evola's book on yoga a few weeks ago, but Vl. Nabokov's name "Lolita" might come from the Tantric name "Lalita", "playful", of the Shaktic goddess of primordial power, expressing her manifestation as free and not bound by any external laws.

Baron Julius Evola has possibly the most amiable "take" on the Crusades as an opportunity for Christian knights and Muslim warriors to offer each other the opportunity of martyrdom and an honorable death in the name of their religions. Both sides fought over "castles in the sky".

I think I have posted this almost word for word but switching from a subjective perspective to an objective one is a very interesting change here. A warrior caste member's goal is to fight and die for his faith. There is a secret esoteric friendship in any outward religious war.

I think this is true but also something that obviously can no longer function once everyone becomes aware of it, it requires a certain type of societal consciousness. Evola also calls von Cusa the greatest European of all time for trying to convert the Sultan stop the bloodshed
